---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Pipeline from '../components/Pipeline.astro';
import { getRelativeLocaleUrl } from 'astro:i18n';

const home = getRelativeLocaleUrl('en', '');

const steps = [
  {
    name: 'Requirements in',
    detail: 'Ingests the PRD as PDF or DOCX — the document the team already has.',
  },
  {
    name: 'User stories',
    detail: 'An LLM extracts user stories from the requirements.',
  },
  {
    name: 'ISTQB test cases',
    detail: 'Generated across positive, negative, edge and boundary classes.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Human approval',
    detail: 'A review gate before anything runs — judgment stays with the tester.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Agentic execution',
    detail:
      'An LLM loop drives Playwright through function-calling tools in a real browser.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Results out',
    detail: 'Jira via Xray Cloud, PDF/Excel reports with AI root-cause analysis.',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="Neotest — LLM-powered QA automation | Chedy Sleimi"
  description="Case study: Neotest, a multi-tenant platform that turns a requirements document into reviewed, executed, reported test cases — an agentic LLM loop driving Playwright, with self-healing locators and deterministic replay."
  path="neotest"
>
  <article>
    <header class="wrap intro">
      <p class="meta">
        Case study · Final-year engineering project (PFE) · Neoalians AI department ·
        <span class="nowrap">March – July 2026</span>
      </p>
      <h1>Neotest: the QA lifecycle, automated — with a human in the loop.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Turning a requirements document into executed, reported test cases is slow,
        repetitive work: read the PRD, derive user stories, write positive, negative,
        edge and boundary cases, keep Jira in sync, then run everything by hand.
        Neotest automates that lifecycle end to end — and keeps a person in the loop
        exactly where judgment matters.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="section" aria-labelledby="h-pipeline">
      <div class="wrap section-grid">
        <h2 id="h-pipeline">The pipeline</h2>
        <Pipeline label="Neotest pipeline, from requirements to results" {steps} />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" aria-labelledby="h-cases">
      <div class="wrap section-grid">
        <h2 id="h-cases">From document to test cases</h2>
        <div class="flow">
          <p>
            Neotest starts where a QA team actually starts: the requirements
            document. It ingests PDF or DOCX, uses an LLM to extract user stories,
            and generates ISTQB-style test cases across the four classes a tester
            would write by hand — positive, negative, edge and boundary.
          </p>
          <p>
            Nothing executes on the model's word alone. Generated cases pass through
            a <strong>human-in-the-loop approval gate</strong>: the tester reviews,
            edits and approves before a single browser launches. The point is not to
            replace test design judgment — it's to stop spending it on typing.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" aria-labelledby="h-exec">
      <div class="wrap section-grid">
        <h2 id="h-exec">Execution in a real browser</h2>
        <div class="flow">
          <p>
            Approved cases run through an <strong>agentic execution engine</strong>:
            an LLM loop drives Playwright via function-calling tools, deciding step
            by step how to carry each test out in a real browser session. Execution
            streams live over WebSockets — screencast, console output and per-step
            status as it happens.
          </p>
          <p>
            Agentic runs are exploratory by nature, so Neotest also has a
            deterministic <strong>REPLAY mode</strong>, and it
            <strong>self-heals broken locators</strong> when the UI under test
            changes. For teams that want plain artifacts, it exports standalone
            runnable Playwright scripts via codegen.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" aria-labelledby="h-org">
      <div class="wrap section-grid">
        <h2 id="h-org">Built for a QA organization</h2>
        <div class="flow">
          <p>
            The platform is <strong>multi-tenant</strong> and speaks the tools QA
            teams already live in: generated tests and run results push to
            <strong>Jira via Xray Cloud</strong> as Test and Test Execution issues.
            Runs export as PDF and Excel reports with AI root-cause analysis of
            failures, and every run tracks its <strong>LLM cost</strong> — you know
            what each suite costs before you scale it.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" aria-labelledby="h-stack">
      <div class="wrap section-grid">
        <h2 id="h-stack">Stack</h2>
        <div class="flow">
          <p>
            Django 5 + DRF, Django Channels / Daphne, Celery, PostgreSQL, Redis,
            Docker · Next.js 16, React 19, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS · LiteLLM
            (provider-agnostic — Claude / OpenAI / Gemini) · Playwright.
          </p>
          <p class="note">
            Neotest belongs to Neoalians, so this case study shows no product
            screenshots or source — it describes, in my own words, the platform
            I built.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" aria-labelledby="h-next">
      <div class="wrap section-grid">
        <h2 id="h-next">What's next</h2>
        <div class="flow">
          <p>
            I'm looking for a junior QA role where this mix — hands-on manual
            testing, Playwright automation, and building the tooling itself — is
            useful from day one.
          </p>
          <p class="cta-row">
            <a class="btn" href="mailto:chedysleimi@gmail.com">Get in touch</a>
            <a class="btn-quiet" href={home}>← Back to the overview</a>
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .intro {
    padding-block: clamp(3.5rem, 8vw, 6rem) clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4rem);
  }

  .intro h1 {
    max-width: 24ch;
  }
</style>
